[From Mod.ML's comment in ProMED-mail post Syphilis - USA (NY) 20070814.2650:

"The total number of cases of syphilis (primary, secondary, and
tertiary) reported annually in the United States declined dramatically
in the 1940's to a low in 2000. As the rate of primary and secondary
(infectious) syphilis (a better indicator of disease activity)
decreased among homosexual and bisexual males, largely because of
changes in sexual behavior due to AIDS, a spike occurred in the late
1980s among heterosexual men, women, and neonates (congenital
syphilis) that was attributed to epidemic of crack cocaine use and
exchange of sex for drugs. Cases of syphilis again dropped from 1990
to 2000. In 2000, the rate of primary and secondary syphilis in the
United States was 2.1 cases per 100 000 population, the lowest since
reporting began in 1941. From 2001 to 2004, the primary and secondary
syphilis rate increased nationally to 2.7, primarily as a result of
increases in cases among men who have sex with men
(<http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5510a1.htm>)."

The causes of the current outbreak in Winston-Salem are at the present
time speculative and require a detailed epidemiologic investigation.
Winston-Salem is the county seat and largest city of Forsyth County,
North Carolina and the fourth-largest city in the state
(<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Winston-Salem,_North_Carolina>). As of
the 2000 census, the city's population was 185 776, with a total urban
population of 299 290. Corporate headquarters of the RJ Reynolds
Tobacco Company, Krispy Kreme Doughnuts, and until 2001, Wachovia
Bank, are located in Winston-Salem, as is Wake-Forest University.

The state of North Carolina can be located on the
HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at
<http://healthmap.org/r/00J*>. - Mod.ML]
